ACCRINT.name: ACCRINT
ACCRINT.long_desc:
Returns the accrued interest for a security that pays periodic interest.

Excel Function:
       ACCRINT(issue,firstinterest,settlement,rate,par,frequency[,basis])

settlement.name: settlement
settlement.short_desc:
The security's settlement date.
The security settlement date is the date after the issue date
when the security is traded to the buyer.

par.name: par
par.short_desc:
The security's par value.
If you omit par, ACCRINT uses $1,000.

frequency.name: frequency
frequency.short_desc:
the number of coupon payments per year.
Valid frequency values are:
    1    Annual
    2    Semi-Annual
    4    Quarterly
If working in Gnumeric Mode, the following frequency options are
also available
    6    Bimonthly
    12    Monthly

basis.name: basis
basis.short_desc:
The type of day count to use.
0 or omitted    US (NASD) 30/360
1                Actual/actual
2                Actual/360
3                Actual/365
4                European 30/360

AMORDEGRC.name: AMORDEGRC
AMORDEGRC.long_desc:
Returns the depreciation for each accounting period.
This function is provided for the French accounting system. If an asset is purchased in
the middle of the accounting period, the prorated depreciation is taken into account.
The function is similar to AMORLINC, except that a depreciation coefficient is applied in
the calculation depending on the life of the assets.
This function will return the depreciation until the last period of the life of the assets
or until the cumulated value of depreciation is greater than the cost of the assets minus
the salvage value.

Excel Function:
       AMORDEGRC(cost,purchased,firstPeriod,salvage,period,rate[,basis])

CUMIPMT.name: CUMIPMT
CUMIPMT.long_desc:
Returns the cumulative interest paid on a loan between the start and end periods.

Excel Function:
       CUMIPMT(rate,nper,pv,start,end[,type])

nper.name: nper
nper.short_desc: The total number of payment periods

start.name: start
start.short_desc:
The first period in the calculation.
Payment periods are numbered beginning with 1.

end.name: end
end.short_desc: The last period in the calculation.

type.name: type
type.short_desc:
A number 0 or 1 and indicates when payments are due:
0 or omitted    At the end of the period.
1                At the beginning of the period.

DB.name: DB
DB.long_desc:
Returns the depreciation of an asset for a specified period using the
fixed-declining balance method.
This form of depreciation is used if you want to get a higher depreciation value
at the beginning of the depreciation (as opposed to linear depreciation). The
depreciation value is reduced with every depreciation period by the depreciation
already deducted from the initial cost.

       DB(cost,salvage,life,period[,month])

DOLLARDE.name: DOLLARDE
DOLLARDE.long_desc:
Converts a dollar price expressed as an integer part and a fraction
       part into a dollar price expressed as a decimal number.
Fractional dollar numbers are sometimes used for security prices.

Excel Function:
       DOLLARDE(fractional_dollar,fraction)

DOLLARFR.name: DOLLARFR
DOLLARFR.long_desc:

npery.short_desc: Number of compounding payments per year

FV.name: FV
FV.long_desc:
Returns the Future Value of a cash flow with constant payments and interest rate (annuities).

Excel Function:
       FV(rate,nper,pmt[,pv[,type]])

nper.name: nper
nper.short_desc: Total number of payment periods in an annuity

pmt.name: pmt
pmt.short_desc:
The payment made each period: it cannot change over the
life of the annuity. Typically, pmt contains principal
and interest but no other fees or taxes.

pv.name: pv
pv.short_desc:
Present Value, or the lump-sum amount that a series of
future payments is worth right now.

type.name: type
type.short_desc:
A number 0 or 1 and indicates when payments are due:
0 or omitted    At the end of the period.
1                At the beginning of the period.

FVSCHEDULE.name: FVSCHEDULE
FVSCHEDULE.long_desc:
Returns the future value of an initial principal after applying a series of compound interest rates.
Use FVSCHEDULE to calculate the future value of an investment with a variable or adjustable rate.

Excel Function:

schedule.name: schedule
schedule.short_desc: An array of interest rates to apply.

IPMT.name: IPMT
IPMT.long_desc:
Returns the interest payment for a given period for an investment based on periodic, constant payments and a constant interest rate.

Excel Function:
       IPMT(rate,per,nper,pv[,fv][,type])

per.name: per
per.short_desc: Period for which we want to find the interest

type.name: type
type.short_desc: Payment type: 0 = at the end of each period, 1 = at the beginning of each period

IRR.name: IRR
IRR.long_desc:
Returns the internal rate of return for a series of cash flows represented by the numbers in values.
These cash flows do not have to be even, as they would be for an annuity. However, the cash flows must occur
at regular intervals, such as monthly or annually. The internal rate of return is the interest rate received
for an investment consisting of payments (negative values) and income (positive values) that occur at regular
periods.

Excel Function:
       IRR(values[,guess])

values.name: values
values.short_desc:
An array or a reference to cells that contain numbers for which you want
    to calculate the internal rate of return.
Values must contain at least one positive value and one negative value to
    calculate the internal rate of return.

guess.name: guess
guess.short_desc: A number that you guess is close to the result of IRR

ISPMT.name: ISPMT
ISPMT.long_desc:
Returns the interest payment for an investment based on an interest rate and a constant payment schedule.

Excel Function:
    =ISPMT(interest_rate, period, number_payments, PV)

interest_rate is the interest rate for the investment

period is the period to calculate the interest rate.  It must be betweeen 1 and number_payments.

number_payments is the number of payments for the annuity

PV is the loan amount or present value of the payments

MIRR.name: MIRR
MIRR.long_desc:
Returns the modified internal rate of return for a series of periodic cash flows. MIRR considers both
       the cost of the investment and the interest received on reinvestment of cash.

Excel Function:
       MIRR(values,finance_rate, reinvestment_rate)

values.name: values
values.short_desc:
An array or a reference to cells that contain a series of payments and
    income occurring at regular intervals.
Payments are negative value, income is positive values.

finance_rate.name: finance_rate
finance_rate.short_desc: The interest rate you pay on the money used in the cash flows

reinvestment_rate.name: reinvestment_rate
reinvestment_rate.short_desc: The interest rate you receive on the cash flows as you reinvest them

NOMINAL.name: NOMINAL
NOMINAL.long_desc: Returns the nominal interest rate given the effective rate and the number of compounding payments per year.
